.SH "NAME"
mkmedia, mksusecd \- create and modify bootable media.
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.sp
\fBmkmedia\fP [\fIOPTIONS\fP]... \fISOURCES\fP...
.br
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.sp
mkmedia (formerly named mksusecd) can modify or create bootable installation or Live media. They can be
either ISO images or disk images (to be used on USB sticks, for example).
.sp
mkmedia supports media in both openSUSE/SLES and Fedora/RHEL layout.
See Fedora/RHEL notes for details.
.sp
The main purpose is to adjust existing media. For example
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
change boot options
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
add boot menu entries
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
update the installer
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
update software used by the installer (including kernel and modules)
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
integrate driver updates
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
integrate add\-on repositories
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
create small network / online boot media
.RE
.sp
\fISOURCES\fP can be directories, existing ISO image files, or RPMs. They are all combined to produce a single ISO.
.br
See \fBSources\fP below for more details.
.SS "General Options"
.sp
\fB\-\-verbose\fP
.RS 4
Show more detailed messages. Can be repeated to log even more.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-version\fP
.RS 4
Show mkmedia version.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-dry\-run\fP
.RS 4
Do everything except writing the final image.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-tmp\-dir\fP=\fITMPDIR\fP
.RS 4
Use TMPDIR as temporary directory (default: /tmp).
.br
Some operations can require a substantial amount of temporary disk space. For example, modifying
the installation system involves unpacking the Live root file system of the installer \- which is typically around 6GB.
.br
Use this option if you would otherwise run out of disk space.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-save\-tmp\fP
.RS 4
Keep temporary files.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-help\fP
.RS 4
Show this help text.
.RE
.SS "Show available repositories"
.sp
\fB\-\-list\-repos\fP
.RS 4
List all available repositories in \fISOURCES\fP.
.RE
.SS "Create new image"
.sp
\fB\-c, \-\-create\fP=\fIFILE\fP
.RS 4
Create ISO or disk image \fIFILE\fP from \fISOURCES\fP.
.br
.RE
.SS "Media type related options"
.sp
\fB\-\-micro\fP
.RS 4
Create image with just enough files to run the installer.
.br
\fBNote\fP: this gives a network installation image which uses the installer from the medium (the typical online media).
For this to work, either the installation is registration\-based or the location of the installation repository must be explicitly set
using the \fB\-\-defaultrepo\fP option.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-nano\fP
.RS 4
Create image with just enough files for a network based installation.
.br
\fBNote\fP: this gives a small network installation image which has to load even the installer via network.
For this to work, the location of the installation repository must be explicitly set
using the \fB\-\-defaultrepo\fP option..
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-pico\fP
.RS 4
Even less than \-\-nano, keep just the boot loader (for testing).
.RE
.SS "Media integrity related options"
.sp
\fB\-\-check\fP
.RS 4
Tag ISO to be verified before starting the installation.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-no\-check\fP
.RS 4
Don\(cqt tag ISO (default).
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-digest\fP=\fIDIGEST\fP
.RS 4
Embed \fIDIGEST\fP to verify ISO integrity, available digests: md5, sha1, sha224, sha256, sha384, sha512 (default: sha256).
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-no\-digest\fP
.RS 4
Don\(cqt embed any digest to verify ISO integrity.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-sign\-image\fP
.RS 4
Embed signature for entire image.
.br
See \fBImage signing notes\fP below.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-no\-sign\-image\fP
.RS 4
Don\(cqt embed signature for entire image. (default)
.br
See \fBImage signing notes\fP below.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-signature\-file\fP=FILE
.RS 4
Store embedded signature in FILE (default: /.signature for SUSE\-style media, no signature file for RH\-style media).
.br
See \fBImage signing notes\fP below.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-sign\fP
.RS 4
Re\-sign \*(Aq/CHECKSUMS\*(Aq if it has changed.
The public part of the sign key is added to the initrd. (default)
.br
See \fBSigning notes\fP below.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-no\-sign\fP
.RS 4
Don\(cqt re\-sign \*(Aq/CHECKSUMS\*(Aq.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-sign\-key\fP=\fIKEY_FILE\fP
.RS 4
Use this key file instead of generating a transient key.
.br
See \fBSigning notes\fP below.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-sign\-key\-id\fP=\fIKEY_ID\fP
.RS 4
Use this key id instead of generating a transient key.
.br
\fBNote\fP: gpg might show an interactive dialog asking for a password to unlock
the key unless you use the \fB\-\-sign\-pass\-file\fP option.
.br
See \fBSigning notes\fP below.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-sign\-pass\-file\fP
.RS 4
Use the password stored in this file to open the key.
.br
See \fBSigning notes\fP below.
.RE
.SS "Initrd/instsys update related options"
.sp
\fB\-\-apply\-dud\fP=\fIDUD\fP
.RS 4
Apply driver update DUD (can be repeated).
.br
See \fBDriver update notes\fP below.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-initrd\fP=\fIDIR\fP|\fIRPM\fP|\fIDUD\fP
.RS 4
Add content of \fIDIR\fP, \fIRPM\fP, or \fIDUD\fP to initrd (can be repeated).
.br
See \fBDriver update notes\fP below.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-rebuild\-initrd\fP
.RS 4
Rebuild the entire initrd instead of appending changes.
.br
This makes the initrd smaller but requires to run mkmedia with root permissions.
.br
See \fBKernel update notes\fP below.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-no\-rebuild\-initrd\fP
.RS 4
Append changes to the initrd instead of rebuilding.
.br
This makes the initrd larger but does not require to run mkmedia with root permissions.
.br
See \fBKernel update notes\fP below.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-initrd\-config\fP=\fIKEY\fP=\fIVALUE\fP
.RS 4
Add config option to initrd intended for linuxrc, YaST, dracut, Agama, or Anaconda (option can be repeated).
.br
The config option is stored in \*(Aq/etc/linuxrc.d/61_mkmedia\*(Aq (for linuxrc\-based media) or
\*(Aq/etc/cmdline.d/61\-mkmedia.conf\*(Aq (dracut\-based media).
.br
See \fBBoot option and initrd config option notes\fP below.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-instsys\fP=\fIDIR\fP|\fIRPM\fP
.RS 4
Add content of \fIDIR\fP or \fIRPM\fP to installation system or root file system for Live media (can be repeated).
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-live\-root\fP=\fIDIR\fP|\fIRPM\fP
.RS 4
Alias for \fB\-\-instsys\fP.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-rescue\fP=\fIDIR\fP|\fIRPM\fP
.RS 4
Add content of \fIDIR\fP or \fIRPM\fP to rescue system (can be repeated).
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-instsys\-size\fP=\fISIZE_SPEC\fP
.RS 4
Resize Live root file system.
\fISIZE_SPEC\fP can be a number, optionally followed by a unit (\*(Aqk\*(Aq,
\*(Aqm\*(Aq, \*(Aqg\*(Aq, \*(Aqt\*(Aq) indicating kiB, MiB, GiB, or TiB, respectively.
If \fISIZE_SPEC\fP starts with a \*(Aq+\*(Aq or \*(Aq\-\*(Aq, the size is increased or decreased, respectively.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-live\-root\-size\fP=\fISIZE_SPEC\fP
.RS 4
Aias for \fB\-\-instsys\-size\fP.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-dud\-dist\fP=\fIDIST\fP
.RS 4
Apply DUDs intended for \fIDIST\fP.
Usually \fB\-\-apply\-dud\fP applies only DUDs that match the product of the installation medium. If you want to
apply a DUD even if the product does not match, set \fIDIST\fP to the dist tag used in the DUD. Examples
are \*(Aqleap16.1\*(Aq (Leap 16.1), \*(Aqtw\*(Aq (Tumbleweed), \*(Aqsles16.1\*(Aq (SLES 16.1).
The option value is actually a shell glob \- so, to catch all, you can set \fIDIST\fP to \*(Aq*\*(Aq.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-no\-docs\fP
.RS 4
Don\(cqt include package documentation files (default).
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-keep\-docs\fP
.RS 4
Include package documentation files.
.RE
.SS "Kernel/module update related options"
.sp
\fB\-\-kernel\fP=\fIRPM_LIST\fP
.RS 4
Replace kernel, kernel modules, and kernel firmware used for booting. \fIRPM_LIST\fP is
a list of kernel or firmware packages.
.br
\fBNote\fP: this option takes a variable number of arguments. So
it may be necessary to terminate the arg list with an explicit \*(Aq\-\-\*(Aq.
.br
\fBNote also\fP: since mkmedia 3.0 this option automatically implies \fB\-\-rebuild\-initrd\fP. Use \fB\-\-no\-rebuild\-inintrd\fP to revert this.
.br
See \fBKernel update notes\fP below.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-modules\fP=\fIMODULE_LIST\fP
.RS 4
A list of modules to be added to the initrd.
Use this in combination with \fB\-\-kernel\fP.
You can prefix module names with \*(Aq\-\*(Aq to have them removed instead.
.br
\fIMODULE_LIST\fP may be space or comma separated.
.br
\fBNote\fP: this option takes a variable number of arguments. So
it may be necessary to terminate the arg list with an explicit \*(Aq\-\-\*(Aq.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-no\-compression\fP=\fILIST\fP
.RS 4
A comma\-separated list of: firmware, modules, squashfs.
.br
See \fBKernel compression notes\fP below.
.RE
.SS "Add\-on related options"
.sp
\fB\-\-addon\fP=\fIRPM_LIST\fP
.RS 4
A list of RPMs that should be made available as an add\-on to the main product.
.br
\fBNote\fP: this option takes a variable number of arguments. So
it may be necessary to terminate the arg list with an explicit \*(Aq\-\-\*(Aq.
.br
See \fBAdd\-on notes\fP below.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-addon\-name\fP=\fINAME\fP
.RS 4
Use \fINAME\fP as the add\-on name.
.br
If unset, the auto\-generated name \*(AqAdd\-On NUM\*(Aq is used, with NUM
set to the smallest number that avoids name conflicts.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-addon\-alias\fP=\fIALIAS\fP
.RS 4
Set repo alias to \fIALIAS\fP.
.br
If unset, an alias based on the repo name is generated.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-addon\-prio\fP=\fINUM\fP
.RS 4
Set add\-on repository priority to \fINUM\fP (default: 60).
.br
Lower \fINUM\fP means higher priority.
.RE
.SS "ISO file system related options"
.sp
\fB\-\-joliet\fP
.RS 4
Use Joliet extensions (default).
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-no\-joliet\fP
.RS 4
Don\(cqt use Joliet extensions. This is useful when there are file names longer
than 103 chars \- which Joliet does not support.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-volume\fP=\fIVOLUME_ID\fP
.RS 4
Set ISO volume id to \fIVOLUME_ID\fP.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-vendor\fP=\fIVENDOR_ID\fP
.RS 4
Set ISO publisher id to \fIVENDOR_ID\fP.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-preparer\fP=\fIPREPARER_ID\fP
.RS 4
Set ISO data preparer id to \fIPREPARER_ID\fP.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-application\fP=\fIAPPLICATION_ID\fP
.RS 4
Set ISO application id to \fIAPPLICAION_ID\fP.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-volume1\fP=\fIVOLUME_ID\fP
.RS 4
Specify ISO volume id of the entire image \- in case it should differ
from the ISO volume id used for the partition.
.br
See \fBHybrid mode notes\fP below.
.RE
.SS "General image layout related options"
.sp
\fB\-\-uefi\fP
.RS 4
Make ISO UEFI bootable (default).
.br
See \fBUEFI boot notes\fP below.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-no\-uefi\fP
.RS 4
Don\(cqt make ISO UEFI bootable.
.br
See \fBUEFI boot notes\fP below.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-uefi\-image\fP
.RS 4
Make UEFI boot image visible in ISO9660 file system (default if it exists).
.br
See \fBUEFI boot notes\fP below.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-no\-uefi\-image\fP
.RS 4
Hide UEFI boot image in ISO9660 file system (default if it does not exist).
.br
See \fBUEFI boot notes\fP below.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-zipl\fP
.RS 4
Make image zIPL bootable (default on s390x).
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-no\-zipl\fP
.RS 4
Don\(cqt make image zIPL bootable (default if not on s390x).
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-gpt\fP
.RS 4
Add GPT when in isohybrid mode.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-mbr\fP
.RS 4
Add MBR when in isohybrid mode (default).
.br
\fBNote\fP: when both \fB\-\-mbr\fP and \fB\-\-gpt\fP are specified both MBR and GPT are
written \- which looks nice but is against the UEFI spec.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-prot\-mbr\fP
.RS 4
When writing a GPT, write a protective MBR (default).
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-no\-prot\-mbr\fP
.RS 4
When writing a GPT, don\(cqt write a protective MBR.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-mbr\-code\fP
.RS 4
Include x86 MBR boot code (default).
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-no\-mbr\-code\fP
.RS 4
Don\(cqt include x86 MBR boot code.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-mbr\-chs\fP
.RS 4
Fill in sensible CHS values in MBR partition table (default).
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-no\-mbr\-chs\fP
.RS 4
Use 0xffffff instead of CHS values in MBR partition table.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-no\-iso\fP
.RS 4
Don\(cqt make image accessible as ISO9660 file system.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-hybrid\fP
.RS 4
Create an image which is both an ISO and a disk (default).
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-no\-hybrid\fP
.RS 4
Create a regular ISO image without extra gimmicks.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-hybrid\-fs\fP=\fIFS\fP
.RS 4
Use file system \fIFS\fP for the disk partition created in hybrid mode.
.br
\fIFS\fP can be either "" (empty string) producing a partition
starting at offset 0 and extending across the entire ISO
image (partitioning tools don\(cqt really like this) or
\*(Aqiso\*(Aq or \*(Aqfat\*(Aq in which case you get a regular partition
with an ISO960 or FAT file system (default: \*(Aqiso\*(Aq).
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-fat\fP
.RS 4
Create an image that\(cqs suitable to be put on a USB disk.
.br
The image holds a single FAT32 partition and it can NOT be
used to write a DVD. You can adjust the file system size
with the \fB\-\-size\fP option.
.br
Technically an alias for \fB\-\-hybrid\-fs=fat \-\-no\-efi \-\-no\-iso\fP.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-size\fP=\fISIZE_SPEC\fP
.RS 4
When using a FAT file system or the \fB\-\-crypto\fP option you can
set the intended size of the disk image.
.br
\fISIZE_SPEC\fP can be a number, optionally followed by a unit (\*(Aqb\*(Aq,
\*(Aqk\*(Aq, \*(Aqm\*(Aq, \*(Aqg\*(Aq, \*(Aqt\*(Aq) indicating blocks, kiB, MiB, GiB, or TiB, respectively.
.br
\fISIZE_SPEC\fP can also be a device name like \*(Aq/dev/sda\*(Aq, in
which casee the size of the device is used.
.RE
.SS "Media repository related options"
.sp
\fB\-\-merge\-repos\fP
.RS 4
When mkmedia detects repositories in \fISOURCES\fP it will try to make
them all available and create a common media.1/products file (default).
.br
See \fBProduct module notes\fP below.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-no\-merge\-repos\fP
.RS 4
Skip the special treatment of repositories and just merge all SOURCES.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-include\-repos\fP=\fILIST\fP
.RS 4
Comma\-separated list of repository names to include in the final image.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-enable\-repos\fP=\fIWHEN\fP
.RS 4
If \fIWHEN\fP is set to \*(Aqauto\*(Aq or \*(Aqyes\*(Aq the included repositories are
automatically added. If set to \*(Aqask\*(Aq the user may interactively deselect
repositories. The default is not to add any repository. Instead, the user
is expected to add the medium as \*(Aqadd\-on\*(Aq during the installation.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-create\-repo\fP
.RS 4
Re\-create and sign the repository (default: don\(cqt).
.RE
.SS "Repository location related options"
.sp
\fB\-\-net\fP=\fIURL\fP
.RS 4
Use \fIURL\fP as default network repository.
.br
See \fBRepository notes\fP below.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-instsys\-url\fP=\fIURL\fP
.RS 4
Load the installation system from the specified \fIURL\fP.
.br
See \fBRepository notes\fP below.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-instsys\-in\-repo\fP
.RS 4
Load installation system from repository (default).
.br
The option \fB\-\-instsys\-url\fP overrides this setting.
.br
See \fBRepository notes\fP below.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-no\-instsys\-in\-repo\fP
.RS 4
Do not load installation system from repository but search for it on local disks.
.br
The option \fB\-\-instsys\-url\fP overrides this setting.
.br
See \fBRepository notes\fP below.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-defaultrepo\fP=\fIURL_LIST\fP
.RS 4
List of comma (\*(Aq,\*(Aq) separated URLs. The installer will try each URL
in turn to check for an installation repository.
See \fBRepository notes\fP below.
.RE
.SS "Boot menu related options"
.sp
\fB\-\-boot\fP=\fIOPTIONS\fP
.RS 4
Add \fIOPTIONS\fP to default boot options.
.br
See \fBBoot option and initrd config option notes\fP below.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-add\-entry\fP=\fIBOOT_ENTRY\fP
.RS 4
Instead of modifying the default boot files, create a new
boot entry. This also means that in case initrd or kernel
have to be changed, the originals are not overwritten but
new files added.
.br
\fIBOOT_ENTRY\fP is the name used for this new entry.
.RE
.SS "Image encryption related options"
.sp
\fB\-\-crypto\fP
.RS 4
If set, an encrypted disk image is created.
.br
See \fBCrypto notes\fP below.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-password\fP=\fIPASSWORD\fP
.RS 4
Use \fIPASSWORD\fP for encrypting the disk image.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-luks\fP=\fIOPTIONS\fP
.RS 4
Pass \fIOPTIONS\fP to the \fBcryptsetup luksFormat\fP command when creating the encrypted volume.
For example, \fB\-\-luks="\-\-iter\-time 1000"\fP.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-title\fP=\fITITLE\fP
.RS 4
The password query screen uses \fITITLE\fP as title (default: openSUSE).
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-top\-dir\fP=\fIDIR\fP
.RS 4
The installation files are placed into subdir \fIDIR\fP.
.br
This helps keeping the directory structure nice and clean
in case you are using the image also for other things. The boot
config is adjusted accordingly.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-filesystem\fP=\fIFS\fP
.RS 4
Use file system \fIFS\fP for the encrypted image (default: ext4).
.br
Don\(cqt be too creative here \- the file system must be supported by grub2.
.RE
.SS "Debug options"
.sp
\fB\-\-mount\-iso\fP
.RS 4
Mount ISO images to access them (default if run as root).
.RE
.sp
\fB\-\-no\-mount\-iso\fP
.RS 4
Unpack ISO images to access them (default if run as normal user).
.br
Note: the ISO image is unpacked into a temporary directory below \*(Aq/tmp\*(Aq.
Make sure that your file system has enough free space.
.RE
.SS "Sources"
.sp
Sources can be
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
existing installation media
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
skelcd\-installer\-<PRODUCT> packages
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
tftpboot\-installation\-<PRODUCT> packages
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
directories with additional or modified files that should be added/merged into the image
.RE
.sp
Sources can be used either as ISO image or RPM file directly, or they can be
unpacked into a directory.
.sp
The order of sources is important. Files from later sources will replace
the same files in previous sources.
.sp
If you pass a skelcd\-installer\-<PRODUCT> or tftpboot\-installation\-<PRODUCT>
RPM (or a directory with the same layout) \- mkmedia will handle these
specially. These packaged contain the complete installation system and mkmedia
will extract the relevant parts to update the installer on the medium.
.SS "Hybrid mode notes"
.sp
Hybrid mode means the image can be used both as an ISO for a DVD or
directly as a disk image. In other words, there is a partition table
added to the ISO image, either GPT or MBR or both.
.sp
If you need UEFI support, you will get two paritions: one for the UEFI
image (the EFI System Partition), one for the entire DVD.
Without UEFI support, you get only one partition covering all files.
.sp
There are two variants this script supports:
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04' 1.\h'+01'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP " 1." 4.2
.\}
Partition 1 is the data partition starting at offset 0 and covering
the entire ISO.
.br
With UEFI support, partition 2 is the EFI System Partition pointing
somwhere inside the first partition to the UEFI boot image file.
This produces an obviously inconsistent partition table and partitioning
tools really don\(cqt like it.
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04' 2.\h'+01'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP " 2." 4.2
.\}
Without UEFI support, partition 1 is a data partition \fBnot\fP starting
at offset 0 but still holding all data files. When you mount it, you see
either an ISO9660 or a FAT filesystem.
.br
With UEFI support, partition 1 is the EFI System Partition and points to
the UEFI boot image. Partition 2 is the data partition. Partition 1 and 2
don\(cqt overlap. In this variant a consistent partition table is written.
.RE
.sp
Normally the file system of the whole image and the file system of the main partition
have identical data and meta data. If you need to have separate labels (volume ids) for
both file system variants you can use the \fB\-\-volume1\fP option to set a different label
to be used for the whole image.
.sp
For a detailed technical description of the ISO image layout in hybrid mode,
see \c
.URL "https://github.com/openSUSE/mkmedia/blob/master/layout.md" "" "."
.sp
There are several options to control the hybrid mode layout:
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
partition table type:
.br
use \fB\-\-gpt\fP for a GPT, or \fB\-\-mbr\fP for a MBR, or use both \fB\-\-gpt \-\-mbr\fP to get
a combined GPT and MBR
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
\fB\-\-hybrid\-fs=\fP to get a partition at offset 0 (as described in point 1. above)
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
\fB\-\-hybrid\-fs=iso\fP to get non\-overlapping partitions (as described in point 2. above)
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
\fB\-\-no\-hybrid\fP to get a regular ISO, not suitable to boot as disk image
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
\fB\-\-no\-iso\fP to get a plain disk image, not usable as DVD image
.RE
.SS "Signing notes"
.sp
On all media there is a file \*(Aq/CHECKSUMS\*(Aq (or \*(Aq/content\*(Aq with the old SUSE
layout) holding sha256 sums of all files relevant during installation. The
file is signed and is used to ensure the integrity of the installation
environment.
.sp
If you modify any file mentioned there (e.g. replacing it or implicitly
as a result of the \fB\-\-initrd\fP or \fB\-\-boot\fP options) \*(Aq/CHECKSUMS\*(Aq is updated and
must be re\-signed. Otherwise the installer will complain when it starts
up. For this, mkmedia will re\-sign the file and add the public part of
the signing key to the initrd.
.sp
You can specify the key to use with either the \fB\-\-sign\-key\fP or \fB\-\-sign\-key\-id\fP
option. \fB\-\-sign\-key\fP must point to a private key file, \fB\-\-sign\-key\-id\fP is a
key id recognized by gpg.
.sp
If both \fB\-\-sign\-key\fP and \fB\-\-sign\-key\-id\fP are specified, \fB\-\-sign\-key\-id\fP wins.
.sp
You can specify a file which contains the passphrase to the key specified with
\fB\-\-sign\-key\fP or \fB\-\-sign\-key\-id\fP to avoid an interactive dialog to enter
the passphrase.
.sp
If there\(cqs neither a \fB\-\-sign\-key\fP nor a \fB\-\-sign\-key\-id\fP option, a transient
key is created. The public part is added to the initrd and the root
directory of the image and the key is deleted.
.sp
The key file is named \*(Aqgpg\-pubkey\-xxxxxxxx\-xxxxxxxx.asc\*(Aq.
.SS "Image signing notes"
.sp
mkmedia can also embed a signature of the checksum metadata into the image.
This can be used by the \fBcheckmedia\fP tool to verify the integrity of the
image.
.sp
The signature is stored in a special file that can be set with the \fB\-\-signature\-file\fP
option. The default for SUSE\-style media is \*(Aq/.signature\*(Aq. If you set the file name to \*(Aq\*(Aq (empty string)
the file is still created but not visible in the file system (this is the default on older SUSE media).
.sp
For RH\-style media, no signature file is used by default. Instead, if signing is requested,
a signature block is created outside the data area of the ISO image. This way signing does not
interfere with integrity checks by checkisomd5.
.sp
You can use \fBtagmedia\fP to display the embedded meta data.
.sp
The details of this embedding are described in the checkmedia documentation at
.br
.URL "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/openSUSE/checkmedia/master/README.adoc" "" ""
.sp
Note that this special signature file is always prepared. But actually signing
the image is not the default and you have to explicitly request it with \fB\-\-sign\-image\fP.
You can also add a signature later using \fBtagmedia\fP.
.SS "Boot option and initrd config option notes"
.sp
The argument to \fB\-\-boot\fP is a space\-separated list of boot options, e.g. \fB\-\-boot "foo=1 bar zap=2"\fP.
If an option is already used in the existng boot
config, the option is modified in place. If it is a new option, it is appended to the
list of boot options. You can also remove options by prefixing them with a minus sign, for example
\fB\-\-boot "\-foo \-bar zap=123"\fP would remove options \fBfoo\fP and \fBbar\fP and add/modify opion \fBzap\fP.
.sp
The boot config is modified in all boot loader config files on the medium.
Notably, on s390x, all parmfiles are adjusted.
.sp
There is some special magic implemented when it comes to boot options than
can validly be specified more than once. For example \fB\-\-boot "console=ttyS0
console=ttyS1"\fP. If a boot option is specified at least twice, it is assumed
that the intention is to have them all added to the kernel command line. In
this case, these options are all added without replacing any existing
option of the same name. If you intend to replace an existing old option
of the same name, remove the old entry explicitly with \fB"\-OPTION"\fP.
.sp
For example, assuming there is an existing boot loader config with options
"console=ttyS0". Then
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04' 1.\h'+01'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP " 1." 4.2
.\}
\fB\-\-boot "console=ttyS1"\fP results in "console=ttyS1"
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04' 2.\h'+01'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP " 2." 4.2
.\}
\fB\-\-boot "console=ttyS1 console=ttyS2"\fP results in "console=ttyS0 console=ttyS1 console=ttyS2"
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04' 3.\h'+01'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP " 3." 4.2
.\}
\fB\-\-boot "\-console console=ttyS1 console=ttyS2"\fP results in "console=ttyS1 console=ttyS2"
.RE
.sp
This magic is turned off if there are quotes ("") used in any place in the boot options. For example
\fB\-\-boot "foo=\(rs"X\(rs""\fP. In this case, the entire boot option string is simply appended to any
existing options verbatim.
.sp
Boot options are often options intended for the installation program. For
example, passing an AutoYaST profile. In some situations this might add up to
quite a lot of lengthy options.
.sp
It is, however, possible to place these options not in the boot loader config but
put them in config files in the initrd. This gives you a pre\-configured initrd that
can be used in various places without having to worry about getting all the boot
options right.
.sp
This is also a possible way to avoid lenghty parmfiles on s390x.
.sp
Instead of \fB\-\-boot foo=123\fP you can use \fB\-\-initrd\-config foo=123\fP. But watch out for the different
syntax if you set more than one option:
\fB\-\-boot "foo=123 bar=abc"\fP vs. \fB\-\-initrd\-config foo=123 \-\-initrd\-config bar=abc\fP.
.sp
Be aware that boot options always take precedence over initrd config options (so the user can
always override settings at the boot prompt). This means that if you intend to move an existing setting
from boot config to initrd config, make sure you remove the option from the boot config.
.sp
For example, Fedora media set inst.stage2 (the installer root file system location) as boot option. To move it to
the initrd, unset it there: \fB\-\-boot \-inst.stage2\fP \fB\-\-initrd\-config inst.stage2=http://example.com/foo\fP.
.SS "Driver update notes"
.sp
Driver updates (DUDs) are archives (typically compressed cpio archives) that describe
modifications to the installation system. In particular a DUD can:
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
update kernel modules
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
change files in the initrd of the installation medium
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
change files in the installation system / live root of the installation medium
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
change files on the installation medium
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
change boot options
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
change installer config options
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
provide updated packages to be installed
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
add scripts to be run before and after the installer runs
.RE
.sp
Not everything is possible in all situations \- check out the driver update documentation
in the link list below for details.
.sp
There are two ways mkmedia can integrate DUDs into installation media:
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04' 1.\h'+01'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP " 1." 4.2
.\}
By adding the DUD (the archive file) to the initrd \- the installer will automatically look for DUDs
in the initrd and apply them. Use option \fB\-\-initrd\fP for this.
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04' 2.\h'+01'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP " 2." 4.2
.\}
By interpreting the DUD content and applying the necessary changes to the installation medium. Use option \fB\-\-apply\-dud\fP for this.
mkmedia logs the changes in files \*(Aq.update.ID\*(Aq (in live root) and \*(Aq.update.initrd.ID\*(Aq (in initrd).
.RE
.sp
The difference between both ways is that the first method applies the DUD during the installation (the same as using
inst.dud=URL / dud=URL boot options) while the second has everything
done before the installation begins.
.sp
This matters for example for kernel modules: in the first method the
original modules are loaded and then the driver update unloads them and
loads the updated modules. While with the second way the updated modules are loaded
right away.
.sp
Also, changes to boot options, the initrd content, or general installation media changes can only be applied successfully with
the second method.
.SS "Kernel update notes"
.sp
Normally, the \fB\-\-kernel\fP option will do what you expect but there are
situations where it may subtly go wrong. So here is a more in\-depth explanation
how kernel updates work.
.sp
The \fB\-\-kernel\fP option accepts a mix of kernel packages and kernel firmware
packages. That is, you can update both kernel firmware and kernel modules.
But there must be at least one kernel package.
.sp
As a special case if there are no kernel firmware packages
specified in \fB\-\-kernel\fP, then the old kernel firmware files are kept (kernel firmware is typically not
kernel version dependent).
.sp
The initrd typically uses a limited set of kernel modules. mkmedia will try to keep the exact list
of modules but that may not be possible due to kernel package changes. mkmedia output will
display the differences.
.sp
If you have to adjust the kernel module list, use the \fB\-\-modules\fP option. Kernel module
dependencies are automatically resolved.
.sp
Note that there may be not just a single package containing kernel modules (e.g. kernel\-default)
but several others (e.g. kernel\-default\-extra, kernel\-default\-optional) or even kmp packages with
individual modules. If you see missing modules, you might need some of these packages as well.
.sp
mkmedia will not add all kernel firmware files to the initrd but only those that are required by
the kernel modules used in the initrd.
.sp
For Live media, kernel modules and firmware are also present in the Live root file system. Kernel modules
and firmware are also updated there but the complete packages are used.
.sp
There are two cases: 1. the \*(Aqnormal\*(Aq case (\fB\-\-rebuild\-initrd\fP is active) and 2. \fB\-\-no\-rebuild\-initrd\fP is active.
.sp
Note that since mkmedia 3.0 \fB\-\-rebuild\-initrd\fP is automatically acivated if \fB\-\-kernel\fP is used.
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04' 1.\h'+01'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP " 1." 4.2
.\}
Old kernel modules / firmware files are removed and only files from packages specified
in \fB\-\-kernel\fP are used. This makes initrd and Live root smaller and exactly reproduces the original
initrd and Live root file system layouts.
.br
This also means that if you forgot to add sufficient kernel firmware packages in \fB\-\-kernel\fP, kernel
firmware files might be missing.
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04' 2.\h'+01'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP " 2." 4.2
.\}
New kernel modules / firmware files are added to initrd and Live root. This means your initrd and Live root file system contain
both the old kernel tree and the new one (making it noticeably larger).
.br
If you included kernel firmware packages in \fB\-\-kernel\fP then kernel firmware files from these packages
are added as well, possibly replacing old kernel firmware files with the same name.
.RE
.sp
In both cases, if you run out of space in the Live root file system, use \fB\-\-instsys\-size\fP to increase the
file system size as needed.
.sp
Note on usrmerge kernels: kernel packages (and kernel firmware packages) come in two variants: older packages
with files stored in \*(Aq/lib\*(Aq and (typically) newer packages with files stored in \*(Aq/usr/lib\*(Aq.
mkmedia will accept both and adjust the package layout to the one expected in initrd and Live root.
.SS "Kernel compression notes"
.sp
For SUSE installation media, kernel modules and firmware files are kept in a
separate squashfs image (\*(Aqparts/00_lib\*(Aq) within the initrd.
.sp
Usually, kernel firmware files and kernel modules are compressed to reduce size.
.sp
In certain situations it may be better to keep individual kernel modules or
kernel firmware files uncompressed and rely on the squashfs file system compression instead.
.sp
Or use no squashfs file system compression and rely on the initrd compression.
.sp
To fine\-tune this, use the \fB\-\-no\-compression\fP option.
.sp
Setting it to \*(Aqmodules\*(Aq will uncompress all kernel modules. \*(Aqfirmware\*(Aq will uncompress
firmware files and \*(Aqsquashfs\*(Aq will turn off squashfs file system compression.
.sp
The current setting is stored in the \*(Aq.no_compression\*(Aq file the initrd.
.sp
For example, \fB\-\-no\-compression=firmware,modules,squashfs\fP turns off compression
everywhere. This results in the smallest compressed initrd size \- but it also results in
the largest uncompressed initrd size.
.sp
Note that any new \fB\-\-no\-compression\fP setting replaces the old setting entirely.
For example, \fB\-\-no\-compression=modules\fP will not additionally turn off compression for
kernel modules but means only kernel modules are uncompressed.
.sp
Note also that you almost certainly do not want to use \fB\-\-no\-compression\fP together
with \fB\-\-no\-rebuild\-initrd\fP.
.SS "Add\-on notes"
.sp
The add\-on created here is just a repository, not a full add\-on product.
If you need the latter, you will have to create that on your own and add
it to the iso.
.sp
Although it auto\-generates a name for the repository, it\(cqs not a very
creative one and it\(cqs probably a good idea to choose one explicitly
using the \fB\-\-addon\-name\fP option.
.sp
The default installation repositories have priority 99. Any smaller
number for the add\-on repository will prefer the add\-on packages even
though the package version number is smaller than in the standard
repository.
.sp
The default priority of 60 is chosen to be between the priority of the
default installation repositories (99) and the repositories created by
driver updates (50).
.SS "Repository notes"
.sp
mkmedia supports media with three different installers:
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04' 1.\h'+01'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP " 1." 4.2
.\}
YaST (SLE\-15, Leap\-15, Tumbleweed)
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04' 2.\h'+01'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP " 2." 4.2
.\}
Agama (SLE\-16, Leap\-16, Tumbleweed)
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04' 3.\h'+01'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP " 3." 4.2
.\}
Anaconda (Multi\-Linux, Fedora, RHEL)
.RE
.sp
Starting an installation is a three\-stage process: (a) kernel and initrd are loaded,
then (b) a program in the initrd (dracut or linuxrc) loads the installation system and
starts the installer and then (c) the installer runs an installation using a software repository.
.sp
Each of the three installation programs has its own way of setting the installation system and
software repository locations.
.SS "1. Repository notes (YaST)"
.sp
YaST supports two types of repositories:
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04' 1.\h'+01'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP " 1." 4.2
.\}
The \*(Aqclassical\*(Aq (old) variant which has a \*(Aq/content\*(Aq file with product meta data and file checksums at the
repo location and package meta data in a sub\-directory \*(Aqsuse/setup/descr\*(Aq.
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04' 2.\h'+01'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP " 2." 4.2
.\}
A repo\-md repository which uses \*(Aq/.treeinfo\*(Aq for product meta data, \*(Aq/CHECKSUMS\*(Aq for file checksums,
and has package meta data in a \*(Aqrepodata\*(Aq sub\-directory.
.RE
.sp
A repository usually also contains the installation system. If so, the
image files are placed in a \*(Aqboot/<ARCH>\*(Aq sub\-directory and the installer
can simply be loaded from the repository.
.sp
But if it is just a plain repository without the installation system the
installer has to be loaded from somewhere else.
.sp
Use the \fB\-\-no\-instsys\-in\-repo\fP option to tell mkmedia that it can be loaded
from a local disk or dvd. It will be searched for on any mountable local
device at startup.
.sp
You can override this using the \fB\-\-instsys\-url\fP option to load the
installation system from any location. Please look at the linuxrc
documentation at
.br
\c
.URL "https://en.opensuse.org/SDB:Linuxrc" ""
.br
for details before using this option.
.sp
The installer normally uses an internal list of repository locations that are
tried in turn. You can change it using the \fB\-\-defaultrepo\fP option. For example,
\fB\-\-defaultrepo=cd:/,http://foo/bar\fP means to check the local dvd drive first and
then try via network at \c
.URL "http://foo/bar" "" "."
.sp
SLE\-15 uses a registration server, it does not use the \fB\-\-defaultrepo\fP setting to locate
the installation repository.
.sp
The \fB\-\-net\fP option is just a short hand for \fB\-\-defaultrepo=cd:/,hd:/,<NET_URL>\fP.
.SS "2. Repository notes (Agama)"
.sp
Use the \fBroot=live:<URL>\fP setting to point to the installation system. The installation system is a
squashfs file system image (ususally \*(AqLiveOS/squashfs.img\*(Aq) found on the installation media.
.sp
The default setting loads it from the local disk or dvd you booted from. You can place it on a server and
load it via network if you want.
.sp
Use either \fB\-\-boot root=live:...\fP or \fB\-\-initrd\-config root=live:...\fP to set this option.
.sp
The software repository location can be changed using \fBinst.install_url=<URL>\fP. Set it either via \fB\-\-boot\fP or \fB\-\-initrd\-config\fP.
.SS "3. Repository notes (Anaconda)"
.sp
Use the \fBinst.stage2=<URL>\fP setting to point to an unpacked installation medium. The installation system
is a squashfs file system image (usually \*(Aqimages/install.img\*(Aq) that is located automatically in the unpacked
installation medium tree.
.sp
The default setting loads it from the local disk or dvd you booted from. You can place it on a server and
load it via network if you want.
.sp
Use either \fB\-\-boot root=live:...\fP or \fB\-\-initrd\-config root=live:...\fP to set this option.
.sp
Note that \fBinst.stage2\fP is typically set as boot option. You must remove it from the boot options if you want to set it via \fB\-\-initrd\-config\fP.
.sp
See \fBBoot option and initrd config option notes\fP.
.sp
The software repository location can be changed using \fBinst.repo=<URL>\fP. Set it either via \fB\-\-boot\fP or \fB\-\-initrd\-config\fP.
.SS "Product module notes"
.sp
In SLE 15 the product is split into several repositories called \*(Aqmodules\*(Aq
(don\(cqt confuse this with kernel modules). These modules are distributed
over several media or in separate directories on a network installation
server.
.sp
mkmedia lets you combine the installation medium together with the
modules you need into a single medium.
.sp
Check the available modules with \fB\-\-list\-repos\fP and then pick the modules
you need with \fB\-\-include\-repos\fP.
.SS "Fedora/RHEL notes"
.sp
mkmedia will by default create media with a Fedora/RHEL\-style hybrid mode
(hybrid GPT+MBR, data partition starting at offset 0).
You can change that to create a SUSE\-style hybrid mode
(partition table with non\-overlapping partitions)
by adding option \fB\-\-hybrid\-fs=iso\fP.
.sp
See \fBHybrid mode notes\fP above for more details.
.sp
Notes
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
You can use \fB\-\-sign\-image\fP to create signed images. The image
signature can be verified with checkmedia. checkisomd5 can only verify the
embedded MD5 sums.
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
You can use other digests instead of MD5 using \fB\-\-digest DIGEST\fP but
checkisomd5 cannot verify these images. You will have to use checkmedia instead.
.RE
.SS "UEFI boot notes"
.sp
There are two ways UEFI firmware finds boot files on our media:
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04' 1.\h'+01'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP " 1." 4.2
.\}
by running the boot loader located below the \*(Aq/EFI\*(Aq directory
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04' 2.\h'+01'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP " 2." 4.2
.\}
by locating a FAT file system image via the El\-Torito standard and running
the boot loader stored there; this FAT file system image contains the same \*(Aq/EFI\*(Aq directory structure
.RE
.sp
The \fB\-\-uefi\fP option refers to method 2.
.sp
Note that this FAT file system image might not be visible on the medium (e.g. KIWI produced media hide the file).
If it is visible, it has names like \*(Aq/boot/x86_64/efi\*(Aq, \*(Aq/boot/x86_64/loader/efiboot.img\*(Aq, \*(Aq/images/efiboot.img\*(Aq, or similar.
.sp
You can control the visibility of this image with option \fB\-\-uefi\-image\fP (to make it visible) or \fB\-\-no\-uefi\-image\fP (to hide it).
If this option is not given, mkmedia will try to keep the visibility as it was on the source medium.
.sp
If this FAT file system image is missing (or hidden) or files in the \*(Aq/EFI\*(Aq directory (on the medium) have changed,
mkmedia will create a new FAT file system image based on the updated \*(Aq/EFI\*(Aq directory content.
.SS "Crypto notes"
.sp
The \fB\-\-crypto\fP option allows you to create an encrypted installation disk.
Note that this image is explicitly \fBnot\fP bootable as cd/dvd (no hybrid
image). It is both legacy BIOS and UEFI bootable, though.
.sp
Everything except the plain grub2 binaries is encrypted on a LUKS
partition. Including the installer specific boot config. So if you for
example put some password into the default boot options via \fB\-\-boot\fP this
is also stored in the encrypted part.
.sp
At the moment only x86_64 is supported. And you have to run mkmedia on a
machine that has grub2\-i386\-pc installed (to get the legacy BIOS setup).
.sp
Unlike the usual setup, grub2 is used for both legacy BIOS and UEFI
booting. So the boot screen really looks identical in both cases.
.sp
The default image size is chosen to leave only minimal free space. To
adjust the image size to your needs, use the \fB\-\-size\fP option.
.sp
\fBImportant\fP
.sp
For this to work, the \*(Aqcryptsetup\*(Aq tools must be available in the
installer\(cqs initrd. This is not the case for older media (prior to
recent Tumbleweed and SLE/Leap 15).
.sp
If you work with these old media you must also add the following two
packages to the initrd explicitly:
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
cryptsetup
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
libpwquality1
.RE
.sp
You can find the required versions on the install medium in either the
/suse/x86_64 or /x86_64 directory. Copy them to some temporary location
and add
.br
\fB\-\-initrd cryptsetup.rpm \-\-initrd libpwquality1.rpm\fP
.br
to the mkmedia command line.
.SS "Configuration file"
.sp
mkmedia reads \f(CR$HOME/.mkmediarc\fP at startup.
.sp
\fBsudo\fP=\fICOMMAND\fP
.RS 4
To access existing ISO image files you will need root privileges.
(It will be mounted.) This entry lets you specify a command granting
you root privileges.
.RE
.sp
\fBsign\-key\fP=\fIFILE\fP
.RS 4
File name of the private key file with the signing key. The
same as the \fB\-\-sign\-key\fP option.
.br
See \fBSigning notes\fP above.
.RE
.sp
\fBsign\-key\-id\fP=\fIKEY_ID\fP
.RS 4
Key id of the signing key. The same as the \fB\-\-sign\-key\-id\fP option.
.br
See \fBSigning notes\fP above.
.RE
.SH "EXAMPLES"
.sp
.if n .RS 4
.nf
.fam C
# create foo.iso from /foo_dir
mkmedia \-\-create foo.iso /foo_dir

# create foo.iso from bar.iso and integrate files from /foo_dir
mkmedia \-\-create foo.iso bar.iso /foo_dir

# create foo.iso from /foo_dir, no hybrid mode
mkmedia \-\-create foo.iso \-\-no\-hybrid /foo_dir

# create foo.iso from old.iso and add some boot option
mkmedia \-\-create foo.iso \-\-boot \*(Aqdebug=1\*(Aq old.iso

# create foo.iso from old.iso and add content of directory foo_bar to the initrd
mkmedia \-\-create foo.iso \-\-initrd foo_bar old.iso

# create foo.iso from old.iso and add package bar to the initrd
mkmedia \-\-create foo.iso \-\-initrd bar.rpm old.iso

# create foo.iso from old.iso and add a driver update to the initrd
mkmedia \-\-create foo.iso \-\-initrd bar.dud old.iso

# create foo.iso from old.iso and add package bar to rescue system
mkmedia \-\-create foo.iso \-\-rescue bar.rpm old.iso

# create foo.iso from live.iso and add package bar to Live system
mkmedia \-\-create foo.iso \-\-instsys bar.rpm live.iso

# create foo.iso from live.iso and update kernel to kernel\-default.rpm
mkmedia \-\-create foo.iso \-\-kernel kernel\-default.rpm \-\- live.iso

# create foo.iso from live.iso and increase Live root file system by 1 GiB
mkmedia \-\-create foo.iso \-\-live\-root\-size +1G live.iso

# create new iso from sles.iso taking an updated installer from tftpboot\-installation\-* package
mkmedia \-\-create new.iso sles.iso tftpboot\-installation\-SLE.rpm
.fam
.fi
.if n .RE
